Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp} for the spaghetti.

In the meantime, peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves} (or use a #garlic press{}). Trim and halve the @green beans{80%g}.

When your pan of water is boiling, add the @spaghetti{180%g} and bring back to the boil. Cook until tender, ~{8%minutes}.

Halfway through cooking, add the green beans to the pan and cook for the remaining time.

Once cooked, pour into a #colander{} and leave to drain in the sink. Drizzle with @oil{drizzle} and stir through to stop the pasta sticking together.

== Sea Bass ==

Once the spaghetti is cooked, heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Season the @sea bass fillets{2} with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Once hot, carefully place your sea bass into the pan, skin-side down.

> TIP: To get crispy skin on the fish, don't move it around when it's cooking skin-side down.

Cook for ~{3-4%minutes} before turning over and cooking for ~{2-3%minutes} on the other side.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw fish. It's cooked when opaque in the middle.

== Sauce ==

Meanwhile, clean out the (now empty) pasta saucepan and pop it back on medium heat with a drizzle of @oil{drizzle}.

Once hot, add the garlic and fry for ~{1%minute}.

Stir in the @creme fraiche{75%g}, @vegetable stock paste{10%g} and @water{75%ml} for the sauce. Bring to the boil, then lower the heat and simmer gently until slightly thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Once the sauce has thickened, stir in the @grated hard Italian style cheese{20%g} and remove from the heat.

Stir the @fresh pesto{32%g}, cooked spaghetti and beans into the sauce and warm through until piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed. Add a splash of @water{} if it's a little too thick.

== To Serve ==

When everything's ready, share the pesto spaghetti between your bowls.

Lay the sea bass fish on top, skin-side up, to finish.

Enjoy!